  "local_port": 42852,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How does ngrok work?",
  "response": "Ngrok is a tool that creates secure tunnels to your localhost, allowing you to expose your local web server or application to the internet. This can be particularly helpful for development and testing, especially when you need to share your local work with colleagues or test external webhooks and APIs. Here's a basic rundown of how ngrok works:\n\n1. **Installation and Setup**: First, you need to install ngrok on your machine. You can download it from the ngrok website and unzip the package. You might also need to sign up for an ngrok account to access certain features.\n\n2. **Running ngrok**: To start using ngrok, you run a command in your terminal specifying the port number of the service you want to expose. For example, if you have a web application running on localhost port 8080, you would run:\n   ```\n   ./ngrok http 8080\n   ```\n   This command sets up a secure tunnel to your local server running on port 8080.\n\n3. **Public URL**: When you run the ngrok command, it provides you with a public URL which can be used by anyone to access your local server. This URL is typically of the form `https://<random-id>.ngrok.io`.\n\n4. **Secure Tunneling**: Ngrok uses HTTPS to ensure that the tunnel is secure. It also supports additional features like basic authentication to further protect the endpoint.\n\n5. **Dashboard and Monitoring**: Ngrok provides a web interface (typically accessible at `http://localhost:4040` while ngrok is running) where you can inspect the traffic flowing through the tunnel. This includes viewing request and response details, which can be very useful for debugging.\n\n6. **Custom Domains and HTTPS**: With a paid plan, ngrok offers additional features such as custom domains, reserved public URLs, and better performance. You can also configure SSL/TLS certificates.\n\n7. **Advanced Features**: Ngrok supports other protocols like TCP and can be configured to tunnel other types of traffic. It can also be integrated with many other development tools and CI/CD pipelines.\n\nBy using ngrok, developers can test applications in real-world conditions, share local projects easily, and facilitate testing by exposing local services to remote clients.",
